'''Dr. Stephen T. Colbert, D.F.A.''' is the fictionalized persona of [[political satire|political satirist]] [[Stephen Colbert]], as portrayed on the [[Comedy Central]] series ''[[The Colbert Report]]''. Described as a "well-intentioned, poorly informed high-status idiot"<ref>{{cite news|author= Solomon, Deborah|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2005/09/25/magazine/25questions.html?_r=1&oref=slogin|title= Funny About the News|publisher= New York Times Magazine.|date= September 25, 2005|accessdate= November 13, 2007}}</ref> and a "self-important [[right-wing politics|right-wing]] [[Pundit (expert)|commentator]],"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mitsloanexperts.com/2011/10/17/prof-evan-apfelbaum-a-blind-pursuit-of-racial-colorblindness-research-has-implications-for-how-companies-manage-multicultural-teams/ |title=Prof. Evan Apfelbaum: A blind pursuit of racial colorblindness — Research has implications for how companies manage multicultural teams |publisher=MIT Sloan Experts |date=October 17, 2011 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> the character incorporates aspects of the real Colbert's life and interests but is primarily a [[parody]] of cable news [[pundit (expert)|pundits]], particularly [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] from [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]].<ref name="Steinberg">{{cite news|author= Steinberg, Jacques|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/12/arts/television/12colb.html?ei=5088&en=262a857c34eb149f&ex=1286769600&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss&pagewanted=print|title= The News Is Funny, as a Correspondent Gets His Own Show|publisher= The New York Times|date= October 12, 2005|accessdate= July 13, 2006}}</ref>

Colbert first appeared as a correspondent on [[Comedy Central]]'s news parody series ''[[The Daily Show]]'' in 1997 and remained a regular contributor until 2005, when he left to host ''The Colbert Report'', a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] show satirizing personality-driven political pundit programs. He has also been featured in a number of other public performances, most notably at the [[Stephen Colbert at the 2006 White House Correspondents' Association Dinner|2006 White House Correspondents' Association Dinner]], and as the author of the books ''[[I Am America (And So Can You!)]]'', ''[[I Am a Pole (And So Can You!)]]'', and ''[[America Again: Re-Becoming the Greatness We Never Weren't]]''.

On April 23, 2014, the character appeared on ''The Daily Show'' to announce that he has clearly "won television" and will be ending ''The Colbert Report'' because he has met his goal. This came after the real Colbert announced he will not be using the character when he replaces [[David Letterman]] as the host of ''[[Late Show (CBS TV series)|Late Show]]'' on [[CBS]] in 2015.<ref name="LateShow" /> The [[The final episode of The Colbert Report|final episode]] of ''The Colbert Report'' aired on December 18, 2014; the character later made his final appearance as a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in the ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]'' episode "Chapter 27".

Colbert's performance attracted widespread critical attention and acclaim, with a reviewer writing for ''[[Time (magazine)|TIME]]'' magazine calling it "one of the greatest sustained performances in pop culture, TV or otherwise."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3641534/colbert-report-final-episode-review/|agency=TIME|title=Review: The Colbert Report Is Dead. Long Live Stephen Colbert!|first=James|last=Poniewozik|date=December 19, 2014|accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref>

== Development and inspirations ==

=== ''The Dana Carvey Show'' ===
Colbert's earliest mainstream exposure came in the [[prime time]] [[sketch comedy]] program ''[[The Dana Carvey Show]]''. While only lasting seven episodes in early 1996, it provided Colbert with roles that would help forge his future onscreen persona. This was largely due to its format of delivering sketch performances directly to the camera. Although they did not air, several sketches inspired by ''[[The Onion]]'' also had Colbert playing a [[deadpan]] anchor delivering the news.<ref>Heisler, Steve [http://www.avclub.com/articles/dana-carvey-and-robert-smigel,29184/ Interview - Dana Carvey and Robert Smigel] [[AV Club]] (June 15, 2009). Retrieved on 5-09-10.</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' regarding ''The Dana Carvey Show'', Colbert noted, "If you have an opportunity to give it right to the audience, there’s a special connection that you make by looking at the camera."

Upon the show's cancellation, Colbert was cast for ''[[The Daily Show]]'' by co-creator [[Madeleine Smithberg]]. This was thanks to his performance as a nauseated waiter on ''The Dana Carvey Show''.<ref>Dave, Itzkoff [http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/10/arts/television/10itzk.html?_r=1 Comedy Ahead of Its Time (if That Time Ever Comes)] ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 7, 2009). Retrieved on 5-09-10.</ref>

=== ''The Daily Show'' ===
{{main|The Daily Show}}

Colbert appeared as a [[correspondent]] on ''The Daily Show'' between 1997 and 2005. During this time, the comedian developed the character that would later form the basis for his ''Colbert Report'' persona, one that its creator calls a "fool who has spent a lot of his life playing not the fool".<ref name="IGN" /> Colbert frequently cites [[Stone Phillips]] — whom he describes as having "the greatest neck in [[journalism]]" — as a source of inspiration for the character, as well as [[Geraldo Rivera]], "because he's got this great sense of mission... He just thinks he's gonna change the world with this report."<ref>{{cite web|author= Berkowitz, Elana; Schiller, Amy|url = http://campusprogress.org/features/375/five-minutes-with-stephen-colbert|title= Five Minutes With Stephen Colbert|publisher= Campus Progress|accessdate= August 14, 2007}}</ref> As a correspondent, Colbert was regularly pitted against knowledgeable interview subjects or host [[Jon Stewart]] in scripted exchanges which typically revealed the character's lack of knowledge of whatever subject he was discussing.<ref name="Steinberg" /> Other ''Daily Show'' correspondents have since adopted a similar style; former correspondent [[Rob Corddry]] recalls that when he and [[Ed Helms]] first joined the show's cast in 2002, they "just imitated Stephen Colbert for a year or two".<ref>[[Rob Corddry|Corddry, Rob]]. Interview with [[Terry Gross]] (March 8, 2007). [http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7773229 Rob and Nate Corddry Find Their Place on TV]. Fresh Air. WHYY. Retrieved on October 28, 2007.</ref>

=== ''The Colbert Report'' ===
{{main|The Colbert Report}}

In 2005, Colbert left ''The Daily Show'' to host a spin-off series entitled ''The Colbert Report'', a parody of personality-driven political pundit programs such as [[Fox News]]'s ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' that center largely on the personal views of their hosts. Because of this enlarged role, the personality and beliefs of the Stephen Colbert character have become more clearly defined over the course of the show, complete with a fictitious [[backstory]] that has been revealed piecemeal in short monologues accompanying a part of the program.

The character Colbert portrays in ''Report'' originated as an amplification of his self-important ''Daily Show'' correspondent. As they developed the character and the show Colbert and his staff began to look at some more specific models.<ref name="Gross">Colbert, Stephen. Interview with [[Terry Gross]] (October 9, 2007). [http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=15116383 Colbert Builds 'Report' with Viewers, Readers]. Fresh Air. WHYY. Retrieved on October 21, 2007.</ref> Bill O'Reilly, whom the character affectionately nicknames "Papa Bear",<ref>{{cite news| last=Day|first=Patrick Kevin|title=Bill O'Reilly snarks on Stephen Colbert's new gig|date=February 19, 2007|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-bill-oreilly-snarks-on-stephen-colberts-new-gig-20140415,0,4551395.story#axzz2z3afIRS7|accessdate=April 16, 2013|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> is the most commonly cited point of reference. In a 2006 episode of ''The Colbert Report'', Colbert remarked that, "if it wasn't for [O'Reilly], this show wouldn’t exist".<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1018 Episode 2011], January 25, 2006.</ref> In adapting the character for the ''Report'', Colbert has also mentioned [[Aaron Brown (journalist)|Aaron Brown]], [[Anderson Cooper]], [[Sean Hannity]], [[Lou Dobbs]] and [[Joe Scarborough]] as having an influence over his performance.<ref>[[Howard Kurtz|Kurtz, Howard]] (October 10, 2005). [http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/09/AR2005100901551.html TV's Newest Anchor: A Smirk in Progress]. ''[[The Washington Post]]''. Retrieved on August 15, 2007</ref><ref name="avclub">{{cite news|url =http://www.avclub.com/articles/stephen-colbert,13970/|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060202094518/http://www.avclub.com/content/node/44705|archivedate=February 2, 2006|title = Stephen Colbert interview|first = Nathan|last = Rabin|work = [[The A.V. Club]]|publisher = [[The Onion]]|date = January 25, 2006|accessdate =July 10, 2006}}</ref> References to the character's abuse of [[prescription drug]]s are believed to be an allusion to [[Rush Limbaugh]]'s addiction to painkillers.<ref name="Gross" />

The nightly in-character guest interviews were initially of concern to Colbert, who worried his character's belligerent nature would be off-putting to guests. However, since the show's debut, he says he has found he is able to "slide the intensity" of his behavior depending on his interviewee's ability to respond to his aggressive approach. Colbert now often cites the interview segment as his favorite part of the show, because it allows him to improvise.<ref>Colbert, Stephen (December 8, 2006). [http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/93 A conversation with comedian Stephen Colbert]. ''[[Charlie Rose (talk show)|Charlie Rose]]''.</ref> Colbert advises his guests to disabuse the character of his ignorance. "Don't let me get away with anything. Don't try to play my game. Be real. Be passionate. Hold your ideas. Give me resistance. Give me traction I can work against."<ref name="Harvard" />

=== Books ===

Colbert is the central character in the 2007 book ''[[I Am America (And So Can You!)]]''. Co-written with [[Paul Dinello]] and the writers of ''The Colbert Report'', ''I Am America'' delves into what the character considers to be the most pressing issues facing America. The book takes influence from the literary endeavors of the character's pundit models, such as O'Reilly's ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' (2000) and Hannity's ''[[Deliver Us from Evil: Defeating Terrorism, Despotism, and Liberalism|Deliver Us From Evil]]'' (2004), which Colbert says he "forced" himself to read as a reference. ''I Am America'' is considered a pure extension of the ''Report''; the written medium allowed the writers to employ different styles, such as long-format arguments, that they could not have used on television. "You can actually spend 20 pages talking about religion whereas in the show, two pages is about as long as we hold any one idea", Colbert explains. In doing this, the writers "discovered things that [the character] cared about that... they didn't know he cared about before".<ref name="meet" />

A character similar to Colbert's ''Daily Show'' persona featured in the 2003 book ''[[Wigfield: The Can Do Town That Just May Not]]'' by Colbert, Paul Dinello and [[Amy Sedaris]]. Russell Hokes, a self-aggrandizing journalist, was voiced by Colbert in both stage performances of the text and the [[audiobook]]. Colbert likens Hokes to his self-important correspondent character, but "more extreme, more self-involved".<ref>Colbert, Stephen (May 13, 2003). ''[[The Leonard Lopate Show]]''. [[WNYC]].</ref>

==Non-fictional elements==
Certain elements of the character are drawn from the real Colbert's personal life. Both the real Colbert and the character were raised in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]; both are the youngest of 11 children; both played ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'' as teenagers; and both are practicing [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} Colbert's own interest in and knowledge of religion, [[science fiction]], and [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' story will often show through in the ''Report''. His character has a chocolate portrait of [[Viggo Mortensen]] (who portrayed [[Aragorn]] in [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' films]]) in a place of honor on his shelf; Mortensen briefly reprised the role of Aragorn in the ''Report'''s September 13, 2007 episode.<ref name="IGN">Ken P (August 11, 2003). [http://au.movies.ign.com/articles/433/433111p1.html An Interview With Stephen Colbert]. ''[[IGN]]''. Retrieved on August 15, 2007.</ref><ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=728 Episode 1017], November 14, 2005.</ref> He also owns a [[Sting (Middle-earth)|Sting]] sword presented to him by Peter Jackson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aoltv.com/2011/11/16/elijah-wood-stephen-colbert-compare-lotr-sting-video/|title=Elijah Wood and Stephen Colbert Compare 'LOTR' Sting Swords (VIDEO)|publisher=AOL TV|accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>

Occasionally, Colbert will mention his real-life siblings on the show. In one episode, he placed his brother Ed, a lawyer who advises the International Olympic Committee, "on notice" for refusing to grant the show the rights to air footage of a dispute between two American [[speed skating|speed skaters]].<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1451 Episode 2022], February 22, 2006.</ref> Ed later appeared at the start of the February 22, 2010 edition advising Stephen on how to cover the [[2010 Winter Olympics|Vancouver Winter Olympics]] since his character doesn't have the television rights to the games. Footage from the [[Richmond Olympic Oval]] was used after Stephen was named a special advisor to USA Speedskating. Generally, journalists covering the Olympics don't have access to the venues unless their employer has the rights to Olympic TV coverage, and can't show moving video coverage of any official Olympic event unless they have permission from the rights holder. When his sister [[Elizabeth Colbert Busch]] declared her intention to run for congress, he mentioned the event. Later, when she was nominated to run against [[Mark Sanford]] and the MSNBC show [[Morning Joe]] declared their support for Sanford and mentioned Colbert, he defended his sister's campaign.

In an appearance at [[Harvard University]] in 2006, Colbert revealed that his character's fear of bears was in part inspired by a recurring nightmare he has had, in which a bear is standing between him and his goal.<ref name="Harvard">{{cite web|url= http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=5550134133036374310|title= A Conversation With Stephen Colbert|publisher= [[Harvard Institute of Politics]]|date= October 1, 2006|accessdate= August 15, 2007}}</ref> The character's [[phobia]], which was initially referenced in the show's first "ThreatDown" skit, was originally slated to be a fear of [[alligator]]s. By the time the ''Report'' went to air, the alligator story was several weeks old, and the writers chose to use a more recent news item involving a bear in its place.<ref name="meet">Colbert, Stephen (October 16, 2007). [http://www.apple.com/podcasts/meettheauthor/mta_07.xml "Meet the Author" podcast]. Retrieved on October 27, 2007.</ref>

After Colbert received an honorary [[Doctor of Fine Arts]] from [[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]], the show began listing his name in the ending credits as "Dr. Stephen T. Colbert, D.F.A." even though using both the [[honorific]] prefix and [[post-nominal letters]] is incorrect. During the show, the character will sometimes refer to the degree and the qualifications he mistakenly believes it bestows upon him.<ref name=doctorate>{{cite web|title=Stephen Colbert Honorary Degree - Knox College|url=http://deptorg.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2006/x12687.html|publisher=Knox College|date=June 1, 2006|accessdate=April 9, 2009}}</ref>

In May 2007, Colbert was voted the "second most influential person in the world" by a ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine online poll. The first spot was taken by [[Rain (entertainer)|Rain]], a young [[K-pop|Korean pop]] star with a large following in Asia and the United States. Colbert then declared Rain his "[[Archenemy|arch-nemesis]]" and began mentioning him frequently on the ''Report''. Colbert filmed a satirical music video poking fun at Rain's popular single "How to Avoid the Sun" and referencing several stereotypical [[Korean cuisine|South Korean dishes]] and products. The one-sided feud eventually culminated in Colbert challenging Rain to a competition on air. After telling Colbert "not to quit his day job", Rain appeared in a short segment on the show and competed (and won) a [[Dance Dance Revolution|DDR]] dance-off with Colbert.<ref>{{cite web|author= Colbert, Stephen|url= http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?collectionId=167949|title= Rain Rivalry|publisher= [[Comedy Central]]|date= May 10, 2007|accessdate= March 18, 2010 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080718054844/http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?collectionId=167949 |archivedate = July 18, 2008 }}</ref> Both have been defeated by [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] in recent polls,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url= http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?collectionId=167949|title= The 2008 TIME 100 Finalists|publisher= [[Time Magazine]]|date= May 10, 2008|accessdate= March 18, 2010 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080718054844/http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?collectionId=167949 |archivedate = July 18, 2008}}</ref> though they still continue to be strong contenders.

On June 21, 2007, Colbert broke his left wrist on the set of the ''Report'' while performing his warm-up for the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nofactzone.net/2007/07/26/avery-reports-stephen-has-been-injured/|title=The Truth Behind Stephen Colbert's Broken Wrist: Injury on the set of "The Colbert Report"|date= July 26, 2007|accessdate= November 8, 2012}}</ref> This quickly became a regular source of comedy on the show as the self-absorbed character requested his audience send flowers, launched a campaign against [[Hollywood]]'s supposed glorification of "wrist violence", and began a "wrist [[Awareness campaign|awareness]]" campaign with "[[Livestrong wristband|WristStrong]]" [[gel bracelet|silicone bracelets]].<ref>{{cite news|author= Stelter, Brian|url= http://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/27/business/media/27colbert.html|title= 2 Out of 3 Anchors Join Colbert in Wrist Stunt|publisher= The New York Times|date= August 27, 2007|accessdate= December 20, 2007}}</ref> Although his wrist has healed, he continues to wear and promote his "WristStrong" bracelets. On August 23, 2007, the cast was removed on air and was put up for auction to the general public, complete with celebrity signatures, on [[eBay]], where it achieved a winning bid of $17,200.<ref>{{cite news|last= Sklar |first=Rachel|url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2007/09/03/the-fruits-of-wriststrong_n_62886.html|title= The Fruits of WristStrong: Colbert Cast Sells For $17,200|publisher= The Huffington Post|date= September 3, 2007|accessdate= December 20, 2007}}</ref> All of the proceeds from both the cast and the bracelets were donated to the [[Yellow Ribbon Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|author= Associated Press|url= http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=3512173|title= Stephen Colbert to Auction Signed Cast|publisher= ABC News|date= August 22, 2007|accessdate= December 20, 2007}} {{dead link| date=June 2010 | bot=DASHBot}}</ref>

Colbert occasionally makes comments that he would also make were he not in character. In an interview with ''The Buffalo News'', Colbert said "The weird thing about my character, even on the show, is sometimes I say what I mean. It doesn't matter to me that the audience doesn't know when that is."<ref>Pergament, Alan (April 10, 2014). [http://blogs.buffalonews.com/talkintv/2014/04/choice-of-colbert-to-succeed-letterman-makes-perfect-sense-.html Choice of Colbert to succeed Letterman makes perfect sense]. ''The Buffalo News''. Retrieved April 10, 2014.</ref>

On June 19, 2013, Colbert came back from an unplanned break where he took several days due to the passing of his mother (Lorna Colbert). He started the show with a tribute to his mother, first with a short biography of her life and followed by an emotional video.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Colbert|first1=Stephen|url=http://thecolbertreport.cc.com/videos/yxgnju/remembering-lorna-colbert|website=http://thecolbertreport.cc.com/|title=Remembering Lorna Colbert |publisher=Comedy Central|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> Colbert was visibly emotional and at the point of tears throughout the tribute.

== Titles and styling ==
The titles and styling of ''Her Excellency The Rev. Sir Doctor Stephen Tyrone Mos Def Colbert, D.F.A., Heavyweight Champion of the World✱✱ featuring Flo Rida La Premiere Dame De France'' are mostly for comedic reasons.{{Citation needed|date=March 2014}}

Stephen Colbert became ordained minister on June 2, 2011, granting himself the title of Reverend.<ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/429521/october-03-2013/the-2013-government-shutdown-wedding-of-the-century-pt--1</ref> Colbert was mock-knighted by [[Queen Noor of Jordan]] on April 7, 2009 <ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/224012/april-07-2009/queen-noor</ref> bestowing him with the title of Sir. He was granted an honorary doctorate of fine arts by [[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]] in 2006 <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1898670_1898671_1898679,00.html | work=Time | title=Top 10 Commencement Speeches | date=May 16, 2009}}</ref> giving him the title of Doctor and use of the suffix D.F.A. ([[Doctor of Fine Arts]]). This title is featured regularly during his segments ''Cheating Death with Dr. Stephen T. Colbert, DFA''. [[Yasiin Bey]] gave Colbert the use of his stage name Mos Def on October 5, 2011.<ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/399066/october-05-2011/talib-kweli---yasiin-bey--a-k-a--mos-def-</ref> Colbert was set to interview [[Mike Tyson]] on July 23, 2013. Tyson did not appear which led Colbert to declare himself Heavy Weight Champion of the World <ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/416829/july-23-2012/interview-no-show--mike-tyson</ref> and grant himself use of the title. The large asterisk in the title is to denote that he did not defeat Tyson in a boxing match. The suffix featuring Flo Rida was added during the segment ''I tried to sign up for Obamacare'' on October 23, 2013,<ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/429910/october-23-2013/i-tried-to-sign-up-for-obamacare---the-shocking-conclusion</ref> where his name on the [[Affordable Care Act|ACA]] form said featuring Flo Rida. Her Excellency was added to the title as Colbert was seated next to [[Michelle Obama]] at the [[White House]] state dinner in February 2014, in which the [[President of France]] [[François Hollande]] was not accompanied by a partner. Because it is customary that the first lady of a visiting nation is seated next to the First Lady of the United States, Colbert proclaimed himself [[First Lady of France]] on February 12, 2014.<ref>http://www.colbertnation.com/full-episodes/wed-february-12-2014-godfrey-reggio</ref>

== Fictional biography ==

Colbert's fictional history is not always rigidly adhered to by the show's writers. The comedian himself says that, "My character's history may not always be perfectly consistent ... There's my bio and there's my character's bio, and then there's my character's history, which is slightly different than my character's bio."<ref name="MaureenDowd">[[Maureen Dowd|Dowd, Maureen]] (October 31, 2006). [http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/jon_stewart_stephen_colbert_americas_anchors America's Anchors]. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. Retrieved on August 15, 2007. {{Wayback|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/jon_stewart_stephen_colbert_americas_anchors|date =20070818095819|bot=DASHBot}}</ref> His early life, prior to becoming host of ''The Colbert Report'', is expanded upon in ''I Am America (And So Can You!)''.

Like the actor who portrays him, Stephen T. Colbert is the youngest of 11 children, born into a devout Roman Catholic family—the character's family was so devout, in fact, they sent their teenage son to an "[[exorcism]] day camp located in Canton, Ohio" when they discovered he liked ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''. In his in-character appearance on ''The O'Reilly Factor'', Colbert stated that he is of [[Irish American|Irish descent]] and only adopted the [[French language|French]] pronunciation of his surname to "get the cultural elites" on his side.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,244882,00.html|title= Stephen Colbert's in-character appearance on ''The O'Reilly Factor''|date= January 18, 2007|accessdate= October 18, 2007 | work=Fox News}}</ref> Colbert has made conflicting statements regarding his middle name, which he has at different times stated to be Tyrone (Colbert's actual middle name), Tiberius (like that of Captain [[James T. Kirk]]), [[Lee Harvey Oswald|Lee-Harvey]],<ref>Colbert, Stephen (May 2007). "Presidential Candidate Questionnaire". ''[[GQ (magazine)|GQ]]''</ref> and Qxyzzy.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/2010/04/07/episode-6046-462010/ Episode 6046], April 7, 2010.</ref>
The character has said he was regularly beaten up in high school, and by the time he left for college he was determined never to be a victim again. As such, on the first day of his freshman year he walked into class and punched the first person he saw (unfortunately, this happened to be his [[ethics]] professor).<ref name="IAAASCY">Colbert, Stephen (2007). ''[[I Am America (And So Can You!)]]''. New York: [[Warner Books|Grand Central Publishing]]. ISBN 0-446-58050-3</ref> He attended [[Dartmouth College]] (instead of his first pick, [[Hogwarts]], claiming that his white owl led them to reject him),<ref>[[The Colbert Report]][http://www.colbertnation.com/the-colbert-report-videos/420234/october-16-2012/affirmative-action-supreme-court-case], October 16, 2012.</ref> and was a member of the ΣΑΕ fraternity <ref>[[The Colbert Report]] March 3, 2014</ref> although his acceptance into the college appears to have been largely influenced by a claimed familial relationship with a wealthy donor,<ref name="IAAASCY" /> and graduated in the top 47 percent of his class with a major in history.<ref>Gordon, Avery. {{cite web|url=http://www.colbertnation.com/cn/stephens-bio.php|title=Colbert Nation bio|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080325224351/http://www.colbertnation.com/cn/stephens-bio.php|archivedate=March 25, 2008}}. ''[[Comedy Central]]''. Retrieved on October 18, 2007.</ref> He has also referred to [[Bob Jones University]] as an [[alma mater]].

Prior to embarking on a career in journalism, Colbert worked as a carnival [[roustabout]] and a construction worker. During the 1980s, he was the lead singer and guitarist of an [[ABC (band)|ABC]]-like [[New wave music|new wave]] band called "Stephen and the Colberts". The comedian portrays his character's younger self in the band's [[music video]], wearing worn jeans, cowboy boots and a spiky hair style. Their only revealed song to date is entitled "Charlene (I'm Right Behind You)", one of numerous references to an ex-girlfriend (and cousin) whom he continues to [[stalking|stalk]] despite numerous [[restraining order]]s.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=67 Episode 2094], July 26, 2006.</ref> This song has been made available for [[music download|download]] for free in the video game ''[[Rock Band]]''. On the May 14, 2008 episode, Colbert claimed to have been the "[[totalitarian]] ruler of [[Malawi]] from 1982 to 1984". He mentions that his wife's first name is Lorraine.

Colbert later moved into reporting, working in TV news for several stations in [[Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]]. Occasionally he will show footage of himself as a "young man" (portrayed by Colbert, wearing a false moustache) working as an anchor at a local news station (WPTS) in [[Patterson Springs, North Carolina]], still displaying his trademark outrage over minor municipal issues in the manner of ''[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]'' correspondent [[John Stossel]]. In 1997, Colbert was promoted to anchor of the Channel 7 News on WPTS Patterson Springs after [[outing]] the previous anchor, Wayne Colt, for his [[cocaine]] addiction. His ensuing investigative reports into Colt's downfall earned him a local [[Emmy]], and eventually a correspondent position at ''The Daily Show''.<ref name="IAAASCY" /> This corresponds with the year the comedian joined the cast of the show.

Colbert often makes digs at the expense of ''Daily Show'' host [[Jon Stewart]].<ref>{{cite web|last= Franklin |first=Nancy|url= http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/11/28/051128crte_television|title= The Spinoff Zone|publisher= The New Yorker|date= November 28, 2005|accessdate= December 20, 2007}}</ref> He has implied a strained relationship with Stewart, in contrast with the real Colbert's admiration for the comedian,<ref name="MaureenDowd"/> and suggests that his departure from ''The Daily Show'' occurred under dubious circumstances. The character has described Stewart as a [[sexual predator]]<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=800 Episode 3008], January 18, 2007.</ref> and has been known to become tearful when his name is brought up.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=2365 Episode 3128], October 9, 2007.</ref> On the other hand, Colbert has also implied that he only got his own show by [[blackmail]]ing Stewart with incriminating photographs.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1308 Episode 3047], April 11, 2007.</ref>

Colbert is described in ''[[America (The Book): A Citizen's Guide to Democracy Inaction]]'', to which he was a contributor while serving as a 'Daily Show' correspondent, as holding the positions of the [[Arthur M. Schlesinger, Sr.|Arthur Schlesinger]] Professor of American Studies at Harvard University,<ref>America (The Book): A Citizen's Guide to Democracy Inaction (Warner Books, September 2004) ISBN 0-446-53268-1, p. 39</ref> and of Chief Defender of International War Crimes at the [[International Criminal Court|World Court]] in [[the Hague]].<ref name="America The Book, p. 92">America (The Book), p. 92</ref> The book also states that he is the seven-time recipient of the
[[Werner Heisenberg]] Prize for Excellence in Theoretical [[Mathematics]].<ref name="AmericaThe">America (The Book), p.121</ref> Paradoxically, Colbert is described as being [[starvation|barely capable of feeding himself]]<ref name="AmericaThe" /> as well as being "[[Narcissistic personality disorder|personally unpleasant]]".<ref name="America The Book, p. 92"/>

His body temperature runs "a little" hot @ 106.2 as measured via the Ear (Colbert Report S10\Ep154 - Sept 16, 2014).

Colbert was mock-[[knight]]ed by [[Queen Noor of Jordan]] with [[List of Middle-earth weapons and armour#Narsil|a prop sword]] from [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|''The Lord of the Rings'' films]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=d916anj01&show_article=1|title=Behind the scenes of 'The Colbert Report'|publisher=Brietbart|accessdate=November 17, 2009}}</ref> on his April 7, 2009 show in exchange for leading the "Colbert Nation" in signing the [[Global Zero (campaign)|Global Zero]] declaration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=12731|title=Episode 5046 (4/7/2009)|publisher=No Fact Zone|accessdate=November 17, 2009}}</ref>

===Retirement from television===
On April 10, 2014 it was announced that the real-life Colbert will be replacing [[David Letterman]] as the host of [[CBS|CBS's]] ''The Late Show'' in 2015. It was also announced that ''The Colbert Report'' will be ending and Colbert will not be using the character on CBS show.<ref name="LateShow">{{cite web |url=http://www.thewire.com/entertainment/2014/04/stephen-colbert-will-take-over-for-david-letterman/360481/ |title=Stephen Colbert Will Take Over for David Letterman |publisher=''[[The Wire]]'' |last=Zuckerman |first=Esther |date=April 10, 2014 |accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref> Following the announcement, the character made a special surprise appearance on the April 23, 2014 episode of ''The Daily Show'' to report that it has become clear to him that he has "won television" and changed the world, the goal he originally set out to do, and thus no longer feels the need to continue. He expressed interest in taking over ''The Late Show'' after Letterman retires but couldn't because "[[Self-deprecation|they already gave it to some fat guy]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/stephen-colbert-goodbye-jon-stewart-daily-show/story?id=23457576 |title=Stephen Colbert Says Goodbye to Jon Stewart and 'The Daily Show' |publisher=''ABC News'' |last=Rothman |first=Michael |date=April 24, 2014 |accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thewrap.com/stephen-colbert-says-goodbye-jon-stewart-daily-show/ |title=Stephen Colbert Says Goodbye to Jon Stewart, ‘Daily Show’ |publisher=''The Wrap'' |last=Molloy |first=Tim |date=April 24, 2014 |accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>

During the [[The final episode of The Colbert Report|final episode]], Colbert accidentally kills "lifelong friend and colleague" [[Grim reaper|Grimmy]] in the final segment of "Cheating Death", after which he becomes immortal and uses his powers to fuel a star-studded celebrity singalong of "[[We'll Meet Again]]", before boarding a sleigh driven by Santa Claus, [[Abraham Lincoln]], and "[[Alex Trebek|the man with all the answers]]".<ref name="ew14">{{cite news|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2014/12/19/colbert-report-finale/|date=December 19, 2014|title='The Colbert Report' wraps up with an immortal, star-studded finale|author=Hillary Busis|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref> At the end of the show, Colbert tosses back to Stewart at ''The Daily Show'', implying that the show's existence was just an extended correspondent report for the program.<ref name="wp11">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/style-blog/wp/2014/12/19/the-colbert-report-finale-recap-ending-with-a-song-celebrity-cameos-and-alex-trebek/|date=December 19, 2014|title=‘The Colbert Report’ finale recap: Ending with a song, celebrity cameos and Alex Trebek|author=Emily Yahr|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref>

== Presidential campaigns ==
=== Colbert '08 ===
{{main|Stephen Colbert presidential campaign, 2008}}

Colbert dropped hints of a potential presidential run throughout 2007, with speculation intensifying following the release of his book, ''I Am America (And So Can You!)'', which was rumored (invariably by Colbert himself) to be a sign that he was indeed testing the waters for a future bid for the [[White House]]. Colbert staunchly refused to confirm or deny his candidacy, stating he had not yet made up his mind and must first talk the possibility over with his family.

Colbert confirmed his presidential ambitions on his October 16, 2007 show,<ref>{{cite news|author= Kurtz, Howard|url= http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/10/16/AR2007101602462.html?nav=hcmodule|title= Primary-Time TV With Colbert the Candidate|publisher= The Washington Post|date= October 17, 2007|accessdate= December 20, 2007}}</ref> stating his intention to run both on the [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] and [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] platforms, but only as a [[favorite son]] in his native South Carolina. In an interview with [[Larry King]] he revealed that, as his running mate, he would consider [[Mike Huckabee]] (who himself jokingly offered Colbert the vice presidential position<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.buddytv.com/articles/the-colbert-report/stephen-colbert-for-vice-presi-15564.aspx|title= Stephen Colbert for Vice President?}}</ref>).<ref>[[Editor & Publisher]] (October 11, 2007). [http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003657754 Stephen Colbert May Run for President—South Carolina TV Invites Him to Kick Off Bid]. Retrieved on October 17, 2007.</ref> He also speculated on the possibility of a Colbert-[[Vladimir Putin|Putin]] or Colbert-Colbert ticket. Colbert abandoned plans to run as a Republican due to the $35,000 fee required to file for the South Carolina [[primary election|primary]]. On November 1, 2007, it was announced that he would not appear on the Democratic primary ballot either, after being deemed ineligible by the South Carolina Democratic Party executive committee.<ref>{{cite web|author= Vogel, Kenneth|url= http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1107/6674.html|title= S.C. Dems reject Colbert candidacy|publisher= [[The Politico|Politico.com]]|date= November 1, 2007|accessdate= November 13, 2007}}</ref> Several days later he announced that he was withdrawing from the race, saying that he did not wish to put the country through an agonizing [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] battle.<ref>Associated Press (November 5, 2007). [http://tv.msn.com/tv/article.aspx?news=282528&GT1=7703&silentchk=1& Stephen Colbert Drops Presidential Bid]. Retrieved on November 13, 2007.</ref>

The show went on hiatus immediately after this as a result of the [[2007-08 Writers Guild of America strike|Writers Guild of America Strike]]. When it returned to air on January 7, 2008 without a writing staff, the character justified his absence by stating that he had taken some time off to have "a good cry" about his failed presidential attempt. He said that he had returned to air in celebration of Huckabee's success in the [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2008|Iowa Caucus]], something for which he considers himself [[Colbert bump|personally responsible]] as Huckabee has appeared on the ''Report'' on numerous occasions to invite Colbert to be his running mate.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=2919 Episode 4001], January 7, 2008.</ref>

Despite having withdrawn from the presidential race, Colbert continued to be referred to as an active candidate in the [[Marvel Universe]]. Colbert '08 paraphernalia appeared in the artwork of various [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] comics,<ref name="ColbertforMarvel">{{cite web|url=http://www.marvel.com/news/comicstories.3547.Colbert_for_President|title=Colbert For President|accessdate=June 1, 2008|date=May 31, 2008|work=Marvel.com}}</ref> and Colbert himself teamed up with [[Spider-Man]] in the October 2008 comic ''Amazing Spider-Man #573''.<ref name="Spiderman573" /> On November 5, 2008, Marvel announced that its fictional newspaper ''[[The Daily Bugle]]'' was reporting Colbert's victory over both [[John McCain]] and [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|author= Thill, Scott|url=http://blog.wired.com/underwire/2008/11/colbert-beats-o.html|title=Colbert Bests Obama, Wins Marvel White House|accessdate=November 6, 2008|date=November 5, 2008|work=Wired}}</ref> Several hours later Marvel released a second ''Daily Bugle'' article correcting its initial reports, stating that while Colbert had won the popular vote Obama had secured more electoral votes, thus winning the presidency. "Oops, our bad", said Marvel editor-in-chief [[Joe Quesada]] of the confusion. "We completely forgot the Marvel Universe reflects what happens in the real world."<ref>{{cite news|author= Thill, Scott|url=http://blog.wired.com/underwire/2008/11/bugle-blows-it.html|title=Bugle Blows It -- Obama Beats Colbert on Marvel Electoral Votes|accessdate=November 6, 2008|date=November 5, 2008|work=Wired}}</ref>

=== 2012 exploration for "President of the United States of South Carolina" ===
{{See also|Colbert Super PAC}}
During the September 28, 2011 episode of ''The Colbert Report'', Colbert consulted his lawyer and they set up his own [[501(c)(4)]] organization, similar to [[American Crossroads]].<ref name="delawareonline">{{cite web|title=Colbert takes satirical swipe at disclosure laws to create corporation in Del|url=http://www.delawareonline.com/article/20111004/NEWS02/110040346/Colbert-takes-satirical-swipe-at-disclosure-laws-to-create-corporation-in-Del-?odyssey=tab|publisher=Delaware Online|accessdate=October 6, 2011}}</ref>  As a [[super PAC]] the organization can raise unlimited sums of money from corporations, unions and other groups, as well as wealthy individuals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/outsidespending/index.php |title=Outside Spending |publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/13/rick-perry-super-pacs-rai_n_925943.html |title=Rick Perry Super PACs Raise Issues of Coordination, Collusion |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=August 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |first=Paul |last=Blumenthal}}</ref>  With Colbert as president of the [[Colbert Super PAC]], the PAC ran several political ads prior to the [[Ames Straw Poll]]. The first ad, titled "Episode IV: A New Hope", told Iowans to [[Write-in candidate|write-in]] "Rick Parry" instead of [[Rick Perry]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Sands |first=Geneva |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/176373-colbert-launches-first-superpac-ad- |title=VIDEO: Colbert launches first super PAC ad - The Hill's Blog Briefing Room |publisher=Thehill.com |date=August 10, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/thenote/2011/08/colbert-sends-message-to-pro-rick-perry-pacs-back-off.html |title=Colbert Sends Message to pro-Rick Perry PACs - Back Off! - The Note |publisher=[[ABCNews.com]] |date=August 9, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailycaller.com/2011/08/13/colberts-ads-advocate-rick-parry-write-in-create-a-straw-poll-mess/ |title=Stephen Colbert &#124; Rick Parry &#124; Ames Straw Poll |publisher=The Daily Caller |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref>  and the second ad, "Behind the Green Corn", supported "Parry" as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colbertnewshub.com/2011/08/12/colbert-superpacs-rick-parry-ad/ |title=Colbert SuperPAC's Debut Vote for 'Rick Parry' Ads |publisher=Colbertnewshub.com |date=August 12, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/blogs/yeas-nays/2011/08/colberts-superpac-releases-another-corny-ad |title=Colbert's SuperPAC releases another corny ad &#124; The Examiner &#124; Yeas & Nays |publisher=Washington Examiner |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2011}}</ref>

During the January 12, 2012 episode of ''The Colbert Report'', Colbert announced his plans to form an exploratory committee to lay the groundwork for his possible candidacy for "[[President of the United States]] of [[South Carolina]]". In the process, he transferred control of the Super PAC to [[Jon Stewart]], renaming it ''The Definitely Not Coordinating With Stephen Colbert Super PAC'', since, according to Colbert's lawyer, Trevor Potter, it would definitely be illegal for Colbert and Stewart to coordinate their efforts in super PAC activities. A [[CBS]] news report called Colbert's run "essentially a joke", saying, "The real significance of Colbert's announcement may be the spotlight it puts on super PACs, into which donors can pour unlimited money in order to support or attack candidates, and thus influence election outcomes. Super PACs were made possible by the 2010 "[[Citizens United]]" Supreme Court decision that effectively classified money as speech".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-57358732-503544/stephen-colbert-isnt-really-running-for-president/ | work=CBS News | title=Stephen Colbert isn't really running for president}}</ref>

Colbert's timing was too late for his name to be added the South Carolina primary ballot, and South Carolina law would not allow for [[write-in]] candidates.  Polling showed that 21% of the potential Republican primary electorate reported they would be "more likely" to vote for former candidate [[Herman Cain]], who remained on the ballot, if that vote served as encouragement for Colbert.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://maristpoll.marist.edu/119-colbert/ |title=18% in South Carolina Kinda Somewhat Likely to Back Colbert &#124; Home of the Marist Poll: Pebbles and Pundits |publisher=Maristpoll.marist.edu |date=January 19, 2012 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> Herman Cain received 6,338 votes in the [[South Carolina Republican primary, 2012|South Carolina Republican Primary]], which was more than all the other withdrawn candidates received combined.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enr-scvotes.org/SC/36831/64075/en/summary.html |title=South Carolina Election Division, Results for the 2012 Republican Presidential Primary |publisher=Enr-scvotes.org |date=January 22, 2012 |accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> On the next episode of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' broadcast on January 23, 2012, Colbert boasted about passing the 1% threshold and for Cain receiving many more votes in South Carolina than in [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2012|Iowa]] and [[New Hampshire Republican primary, 2012|New Hampshire]]. Colbert then announced that he would no longer be exploring a run for President of the United States of South Carolina.

== Characteristics ==

Described as a "caustic right-wing [[bullying|bully]]",<ref>{{cite web|author= Sternbergh, Adam|url= http://nymag.com/news/politics/22322/|title= Stephen Colbert Has America By The Ballots|publisher= [[New York (magazine)|New York Magazine]]|date= October 16, 2006|accessdate= August 15, 2007}}</ref> an "arch-[[conservative]] blowhard",<ref>{{cite web|author= Mnookin, Seth|url= http://www.vanityfair.com/fame/features/2007/10/colbert200710|title= The Man in the Irony Mask|publisher= [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date= October 2007|accessdate= December 9, 2007}}</ref> and by his creator and namesake as a "well-intentioned, poorly informed, high status idiot", Colbert is [[egomania]]cal, [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] and fiercely [[anti-intellectualism|anti-intellectual]]. He claims to be [[political independent|politically independent]], like his idol Bill "Papa Bear" O'Reilly; although in fact the character fawns over the [[George W. Bush administration|Bush administration]] and the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], and frequently asks his guests, "[[George W. Bush|George Bush]]: Great president, or the ''greatest'' president?" Since the election of [[Barack Obama]], Colbert continues his right-wing views, but claims he will "support our new President as long as [he] remains popular". Colbert emphasizes that his character is genuinely well-meaning and wants to do the right thing, but does not have the tools to achieve it "because he has no curiosity, he doesn't like to read and he won't listen to anybody except the voices in his head".<ref>{{cite news|last= Colbert |first=Stephen|url= http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0710/14/lkl.01.html|title= Larry King Live: Interview with Stephen Colbert|publisher= CNN|date= October 14, 2007|accessdate= December 20, 2007}}</ref>

[[Image:Colbert report.jpg|thumb|left|The "Eagle's Nest", with its many references to Colbert, reflects the character's self-aggrandizing style.]]

Colbert is deeply self-centered and takes everything personally, a trait which is reflected in his discussion of the news and current events. According to the comedian, "There's nothing too large that doesn't involve him. Every news story is really about him ... Everything he cares about is a news story because he cares about it." This is expressed in his frequent attacks on and feuds with well-known figures such as [[The Decemberists]], [[Sean Penn]], [[Conan O'Brien]], [[Rain (entertainer)|Rain]], [[Barry Manilow]], [[Tony Bennett]], and [[Don Rickles]] (the latter three of whom beat out Colbert for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Best Individual in a Variety or Music Program]] at the [[Emmys]]). The comedian equates these feuds with Bill O'Reilly's [[culture war]]s.<ref name="Gross" />

Central to Colbert's personality is his rigid belief that "what I say is right, and [nothing] anyone else says could possibly be true",<ref name="avclub" /> regardless of any evidence to the contrary. He discussed this in the ''Report'''s first [[Wørd]] segment, using the term "[[truthiness]]" as he explained what he perceives to be the difference between "those who think with their head and those who ''know'' with their ''heart''".<ref>The Colbert Report, [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=662 Episode 1001], October 17, 2005.</ref> He has further gone on to ascribe "truthiness" to other institutions including [[Wikipedia]], which he believes upholds his view that reality can be determined by consensus opinion, and often encourages viewers to use Wikipedia to "change reality". Colbert believes that if a majority of people want something to be true, that thing therefore must become the truth. For instance, after months of scoffing at [[global warming]], Colbert suddenly reversed his position, conceding its existence only due to the [[box office]] success of ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'', a sign that "the [[free market]] has spoken".

Colbert describes himself as [[Race-blind|racially color-blind]] and unable to visually identify a person's [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]],<ref>Pastorek, Whitney (2007). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20043289_20043293_20045778_2,00.html Birth of a Colbert Nation.] ''EW''. Retrieved on December 20, 2007.</ref> explaining, "Now, I don't see race ... People tell me I'm white, and I believe them, because I own a lot of [[Jimmy Buffett]] albums."<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=438 Episode 2138], November 2, 2006.</ref> His race-blindness is a recurring joke, and this statement is often repeated on the show with different punch lines.<ref>Other punch lines include: [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1157 ...because I have my own late night talk show], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1403 ...because I can’t say the "N" word], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1017 ...because I think Barack Obama is black], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=544 ...because I shop at Eddie Bauer], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=566 ...because I belong to an all-white country club]</ref> For this same reason he believed that he was black when he had an emotional breakdown after watching Obama's inauguration video. He later qualified these statements in his book, stating, "When I say I don't see race, I mean I don't see [[Black people]]. But I can spot a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] at a hundred paces."<ref name="IAAASCY" /> Despite all these claims, Colbert often boasts that he has a large number of [[Tokenism|token]] minority friends (including Jon Stewart as "[his] [[Jew]]ish friend" and [[Oprah Winfrey]] as "[his] [[African American|black]] friend"), although in the photos shown these friends appear decidedly uninterested in him. He has stated a similar inability to distinguish between the sexes, claiming to only "see an American". This comes in contradiction of his at times [[sexist]] behavior, for instance, calling only on men during an open discussion with his audience on women's issues.

The comedian has said that he likes playing weak characters, and particularly revealing weaknesses in high status figures.<ref>Plume, Ken (August 11, 2006). [http://www.tibbysbowl.com/bowl/2009/01/05/stephen-colbert-interview/ Interview: Stephen Colbert]. ''Tibby's Bowl''. Retrieved on December 20, 2007.</ref> During the course of the show, he will frequently peel back the Colbert character's apparent bravado to expose a very weak inner core. In one instance, Colbert demands one of his staff members subject him to simulated [[waterboarding]], only to break down into pleas for mercy upon hearing a water bottle cap popped.<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=476 Episode 2143], November 13, 2006.</ref> In another episode, he criticizes ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'' cohost [[Matt Lauer]] for saying that it's unacceptable for men to cry, only to sob hysterically upon learning that [[Katie Couric]] has left the show. These [[status shift]]s occur commonly, and constitute a central component of the show's comedy.<ref name="Harvard" />

Colbert frequently uses his show as a platform for promoting his own fictional merchandise, including colognes,<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?videoId=72801 Episode 2102], August 10, 2006.</ref> science fiction novels,<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.nofactzone.net/?p=1763 Episode 1763], April 18, 2006.</ref> medication,<ref>[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?videoId=86504 Episode 3061], May 7, 2007.</ref> and his own [[sperm]].<ref>.[[The Colbert Report]], [http://www.comedycentral.com/colbertreport/videos.jhtml?videoId=84630 Episode 3045], April 9, 2007.</ref>

== 2009 visit to Baghdad, Iraq ==
[[File:Army.mil-40677-2009-06-11-130625 Colbert haircut.jpg|thumb|left|Colbert receives an "Army" haircut, from Four-Star General [[Ray Odierno]], during filming.]]
Stephen Colbert arrived in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]] on June 5, 2009, to film a week of shows called "Operation Iraqi Stephen: [[Going Commando]]". The episodes were filmed June 7–9, 2009, which was sponsored by the [[USO]] (United Service Organizations).<ref name="USOIraq">{{cite news |title=Bob Hope's Spirit, but No Cheesecake |author=Alessandra Stanley |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/12/arts/television/12watch.html |newspaper=New York Times |date=June 11, 2009 |accessdate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Al-Faw Palace]]'s rotunda was used for the filming of Operation Iraqi Stephen. Stephen had a suit tailored for him in the [[Army Combat Uniform]] pattern and went through an abbreviated version of the [[United States Army|Army]]'s [[Recruit training|basic training]] regimen.<ref>{{cite news |title=Colbert Goes Commando in Iraq |author=Lee Farran |url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=7781207&page=1#.UDwii6lmRNs |newspaper=ABC News |date=June 8, 2009 |accessdate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> The suit was specially tailored by Brooks Brothers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stephen Colbert and Brooks Brothers Invade Iraq |author=Bill Bradley |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2009/06/stephen-colbert-and-brooks-brothers-invade-iraq |newspaper=Vanity Fair |date=June 9, 2009 |accessdate=August 27, 2012}}</ref> As a tribute to [[Bob Hope]], Colbert brought a [[golf club]] on stage, a Hope trademark.<ref name="USOIraq" />

The first episode included an interview with [[Multinational Force - Iraq]] commander General [[Raymond T. Odierno|Ray Odierno]], which was interrupted by U.S. President [[Barack Obama]].  Obama stated that if Colbert really wanted to be a soldier, along with his attendance to Basic Combat Training, he needed to have his hair shaved off. Obama then ordered General Odierno to "shave that man's head".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/08/arts/television/08colb.html | work=The New York Times | title=In Iraq, Colbert Does His Shtick for the Troops | first=Campbell | last=Robertson | date=June 8, 2009 | accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref>  General Odierno then began to shave Colbert's head; the job was finished during the commercial break by one of Colbert's staff members. One Army major said that "shaving of the hair is an amazing show of support" that was "very touching."<ref>{{cite news|last=Karadsheh|first=Jomana|title=In Iraq, Colbert gets military haircut to show his solidarity|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/06/07/colbert.iraq/|publisher=Cable News Network|accessdate=August 7, 2013|date=June 8, 2009}}</ref>  The episode also featured a message to the troops from U.S. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] with a friendly reminder to "always remember to clean your [[musket]]s", a lesson he claimed to have learned at [[Valley Forge]], as a reference to old age jokes that he faced during the 2008 Presidential Election.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/06/07/colbert.iraq/index.html | work=CNN | title=In Iraq, Colbert gets military haircut to show his solidarity - CNN.com | accessdate=May 24, 2010 | date=June 8, 2009}}</ref> Several other prominent politicians, including former presidents [[Bill Clinton]], [[George H. W. Bush]], and [[George W. Bush]], along with Vice President [[Joe Biden]] and then Alaska governor [[Sarah Palin]] recorded messages for the troops that were aired in the following episodes.

